data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new implicit span conversions. In your expression tree, `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>` parameters, so this fails at runtime.

## How to fix it

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the compiler from choosing the span overload, keeping the expression tree valid.
